            "answerKey": {
              "assessmentType": "multiplechoice",
              "answers": {
                "answer_3": {
                  "score": 0.0,
                  "response": "Roosevelt’s call for America to become “the great arsenal of democracy” seemed straightforward enough, but he acted deviously by calling it Lend-Lease and comparing it to loaning a neighbor a garden hose to put out a fire. In 1941, Congress gave President Franklin D. Roosevelt the authority to sell, lend, lease, or transfer war materials to any country whose defense he declared vital to that of the United States."
